    publishedAt: "2026-02-12",
    markets: ["FI"],
    content: "Finland's gambling market has long been one of the most distinctive in Europe, operating under a state monopoly system managed by Veikkaus Oy. As the sole licensed gambling operator in Finland, Veikkaus has held exclusive rights to provide lottery, sports betting, and casino games — both online and in physical venues. However, 2026 marks a pivotal moment as Finland moves toward opening its market to licensed private operators.\n\nThe monopoly system was originally justified on public health grounds. By concentrating all gambling under state control, the Finnish government argued it could better manage gambling-related harm while directing profits toward public benefit. Veikkaus has indeed contributed billions of euros to Finnish culture, sports, science, and social welfare over the decades. However, the monopoly has faced increasing criticism on several fronts.\n\nFirst, the European Commission has repeatedly questioned whether Finland's gambling monopoly is compatible with EU internal market rules. While member states are allowed to restrict gambling for public interest reasons, they must demonstrate that the monopoly genuinely reduces gambling-related harm — a claim that is undermined when the monopoly operator actively markets its services to increase revenue.\n\nSecond, an estimated 40-50% of Finnish online gambling spending goes to offshore operators, which are technically illegal but widely used. These offshore casinos offer larger game selections, bigger bonuses, and features that Veikkaus does not match. The government's inability to prevent this leakage has weakened the public health justification for the monopoly.\n\nThird, gambling addiction rates in Finland have not decreased under the monopoly system. Studies suggest that approximately 3% of the Finnish adult population experiences some degree of gambling-related harm, a figure comparable to countries with open licensing systems. Critics argue that a regulated multi-operator market with proper oversight could achieve better harm-prevention outcomes than a monopoly.\n\nThe reform process began in earnest in 2023, when the Finnish government announced its intention to transition from a monopoly to a licensing system. Legislation is expected to take effect in 2027, with a transition period allowing Veikkaus to continue operating while private operators apply for licences. The proposed framework draws on best practices from Sweden, Denmark, and the Netherlands.\n\nUnder the planned licensing system, private operators will need to obtain a licence from a new Finnish gambling authority. Key requirements are expected to include a physical presence or registered representative in Finland, integration with a national self-exclusion register, Finnish-language customer support, compliance with Finnish responsible gambling standards, and payment of a licensing fee and gambling tax.\n\nFor Finnish players, the transition promises several benefits. Greater competition should lead to better bonuses, faster payouts, and larger game libraries. A regulated multi-operator market will also provide consumer protections that are currently absent for the many Finns who play at offshore sites. Licensed operators will be required to segregate player funds, submit to regular audits, and participate in the national dispute resolution system.\n\nHowever, there are also risks. The Swedish experience shows that opening a market does not automatically solve gambling harm — in fact, some metrics worsened in Sweden's first years of regulation before improved enforcement brought them under control. Finland will need robust regulatory capacity from day one to avoid similar growing pains.\n\nIn the meantime, Finnish players face a complicated legal landscape. Playing at offshore casinos is not technically illegal for the player, but these sites operate without Finnish regulatory oversight. Veikkaus offers a safe but limited experience with no deposit bonuses and a game library that, while expanding, remains smaller than what competitors offer. Our guide helps Finnish players navigate this transitional period and will be updated as the legislative process progresses.",
